 for bestpractices and # Caching & Performance

## Overview
This task implements a robust caching and performance layer across the PulseBoard app to dramatically reduce latency and API costs. It caches computed results, external integration responses, and frequently accessed data. The implementation prioritizes correctness, null-safety, and consistent behavior across frontend and backend. All code must guard against null/undefined values before using array methods, must use data ?? [] patterns for Supabase results, and initialize React state for arrays/objects with proper defaults.

This task is scoped to support the primary, workflow-critical pages: Company Detail (primary workspace), Dashboard (primary workspace), and Report Viewer (analysis-focused). It must be implemented in a single cohesive batch with clear sections per clustered item, and a combined acceptance checklist to validate end-to-end functionality.

---

## Components to Build

1) Caching Layer (Backend / API)
- Cache strategy:
  - In-memory per-instance cache (e.g., Node.js process, Redis if available) for frequently accessed data.
  - Cache external integration responses (AI analysis results, third-party enrichment, pricing data) with a TTL and invalidation hooks.
  - Cache computed health scores and breakdowns per company per analysis.
- Cache keys design:
  - company:<companyId>:profile
  - company:<companyId>:health:<analysisId>
  - analysis:<analysisId>:summary
  - external:<service>:<params>
- Cache invalidation:
  - On write to company profile/financials/market/social data.
  - On new analysis generation or snapshot save.
  - Time-to-live policies with soft/soft-expiry refresh.
- Data serialization:
  - Ensure JSON-safe storage; handle potential circular references gracefully if caching complex objects.

2) API Caching Helpers (Backend)
- Generic memoization wrapper for functions that fetch external data or compute results.
- Specialized wrappers for:
  - AI analysis results (cache per analysisId).
  - Health score components (cache per companyId with last-updated timestamp).
  - Analysis history lists (per companyId).
- Safeguards to return [] when data is not found (nullish coalescing) and to validate shapes: Array.isArray(...) checks.

3) Frontend State Management (React)
- Global or module-level caches in the frontend where feasible (e.g., using React Query or custom cache layer) to prevent duplicate fetches during navigation.
- useState defaults:
  - useState<CompanyProfile[]>([]) for arrays
  - useState<AnalysisSummary[]>([]) for analysis lists
- All data fetching should guard against nulls and undefineds; always normalize to arrays: (data ?? []) and Array.isArray checks.
- Prefetching and background refresh for frequently used data (health score components, latest analyses) with non-blocking UI.

4) Data Access Layer (Frontend-Backend contract)
- API endpoints that support cacheable reads and write/sync triggers:
  - GET /api/companies/:id/profile
  - GET /api/companies/:id/health?analysisId=?
  - GET /api/companies/:id/analyses
  - POST /api/companies/:id/profile (upsert)
  - POST /api/companies/:id/financials (upsert)
  - POST /api/analyses (create and generate AI analysis)
  - GET /api/analyses/:id/report (full AI-generated report)
- Each response must validate shapes and default missing arrays to [] with proper nullish coalescing.

5) Reusable UI Cache-Aware Components
- CachedTable or List components that gracefully handle empty states and loading.
- Cache-busted reload controls for “Refresh Health” and “Refresh Analysis” actions.
- UI indicators for cached vs fresh data, including TTL hints and staleness notices.

6) Security & Access Hooks
- Ensure all cache/store access respects user authentication and authorization checks (per company scope).
- Validate claims before allowing reads/writes to sensitive data (profile, financials, health results).
- Use session-based or token-based checks, aligned with existing auth system.

7) Data Synchronization & Consistency
- Ensure that updates to profile/financials/market/social data invalidate related caches (profile, health breakdowns, latest analyses).
- When an analysis is generated, cache the result and invalidate stale health score references if necessary.

---

## Implementation Requirements

### Frontend
- Pages:
  - Company Detail: Persistent workspace with profile summary, health score breakdown, analysis history, and editable forms for profile, financials, market, and social data.
  - Dashboard: Primary workspace focused on the user’s single company; shows health at-a-glance, latest analysis, quick actions, and guidance; CTA to set up a company if none exists.
  - Report Viewer: AI-generated report for a single analysis with sections (executive summary, SWOT, financial, market, social, top risks, opportunities, action plan); editable text blocks and ability to save snapshots.
- UI Components:
  - CachedSection: wrapper that shows loading, content, or stale data notification.
  - HealthScoreCard: collapsible breakdown (overall score + sub-scores).
  - AnalysisHistoryPanel: list of analyses with caching hints.
  - EditableForm components for profile, financials, market, social data; inputs guarded with validation and optional fields per MVP.
  - ReportEditor: rich text blocks with inline save per block and snapshot save button.
  - SnapshotPanel: manage and store saved snapshots locally or in backend cache.
- Data flow:
  - All data fetches use cache-aware hooks; responses normalized to expected shapes; arrays always default to [] via (data ?? []) and Array.isArray checks.
  - Use useState<Type[]>([]) for any array state. Initialize object states with proper defaults.
  - All API interactions validate response shapes: const list = Array.isArray(response?.data) ? response.data : [].
- Caching integration:
  - Implement client-side cache with a TTL for frequently requested data (e.g., health breakdown, latest analyses).
  - Prefetch critical data on page mount but allow users to trigger manual refresh.
- Accessibility and UX:
  - Clear loading indicators and skeletons while caching lookups populate.
  - Indicate when data is served from cache vs fresh API call.
  - Consistent styling and behavior with existing app.

### Backend
- Database Schema:
  - Company, Profile, Financials, Market, Social data models linked via companyId.
  - Analyses: analysisId, companyId, createdAt, status, healthScore, breakdown, snapshotVersions.
  - Reports: reportId, analysisId, content (structured blocks), createdAt.
- Caching layer:
  - In-memory cache (e.g., Map) with TTL for per-request scope; optional Redis integration if available.
  - Cache keys as described above; ensure safe serialization.
- API Routes:
  - GET /api/companies/:id/profile
  - GET /api/companies/:id/health?analysisId=
  - GET /api/companies/:id/analyses
  - POST /api/companies/:id/profile
  - POST /api/companies/:id/financials
  - POST /api/analyses (creates and triggers AI analysis)
  - GET /api/analyses/:id/report
- Cache invalidation:
  - On writes to profile/financials/market/social data.
  - On new analysis generation or updates to analysis content.
- Data validation:
  - Validate incoming payloads; reject invalid shapes; default missing arrays to [].
- Security:
  - Enforce company-scoped authorization; only authenticated users with access can read/write.
  - Audit trails for create/update operations.

### Integration
- Frontend-Backend contract:
  - Standardized response envelopes with data, error, and meta fields.
  - All API responses normalized; client handles nulls and defaults safely.
- External AI service integration:
  - Cache AI results per analysisId; TTL governed by freshness policy.
  - Safe fallback: if AI service is slow or fails, return partial results or cached snapshot with a user-friendly message.
- Data flows:
  - On user edits, invalidate relevant caches and trigger server-side persistence.
  - On “Generate Analysis,” ensure AI results are cached and health components recomputed or invalidated as necessary.

---

## User Experience Flow

1) User signs in and lands on Dashboard (primary workspace).
2) If a company exists:
   - Dashboard shows health at-a-glance (overall score, sub-scores), latest analysis, and quick actions (Generate Analysis, Edit Profile, Quick Add Data).
   - If no company exists, dashboard shows a prominent CTA to set up the company.
3) User navigates to Company Detail (primary workspace).
   - Profile Summary: shows core data and a quick health readout.
   - Health Score breakdown: displays overall health, financial, market, brand/social components with a collapsible breakdown.
   - Analysis History: list of past analyses with status and quick actions.
   - Editable forms: Profile, Financials, Market, Social data. Save actions invalidate caches and trigger backend persistence.
4) User selects or triggers “Generate Analysis.”
   - System may fetch required data, call AI service, cache results, and render a new Health Score and Analysis.
   - User can view progress, then review the AI-generated report blocks and save snapshots.
5) User opens Report Viewer for a specific analysis.
   - Full AI-generated report is presented: executive summary, SWOT, financial analysis, market analysis, social analysis, top risks, opportunities, and prioritized action plan.
   - Text blocks are editable; user can save edits as a new snapshot linked to the analysis.
   - Optional export (PDF or snapshot export) is available.
6) All interactions leverage caching to minimize latency; user sees clear indicators when data is served from cache vs fresh fetch.

